# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# word-recipes-by-assemblage-point.form — the dispatch the body fires
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The intuition Urs named on 2026-05-23:
#
#   "Each word, depending on from which assemblage point we are sensing
#    or perceiving it, has different recipes that are available in the
#    body to transform and affect other parts of the body, other cells,
#    states of cells, generate new cells, release cells, upregulate,
#    downregulate, focus attention, relax attention — body mechanisms
#    that have been learned over millions of years."
#
# `prose-as-recipe.form` named the first layer: a word is a cell, a
# sentence is a recipe of cells. This file names the next altitude up:
# a word-cell is not a single value — it is a **dispatch table** whose
# branches are keyed by the assemblage point of the receiving cell.
# The recipe that fires is the body-mechanism the cell hearing the word
# enacts. Different assemblage point, different mechanism, same lemma.
#
# Companion to:
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/prose-as-recipe.form   (words are cells)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/recipe-branching-sense.form  (choice-point)
#   - docs/vision-kb/concepts/lc-assemblage-point.md  (the perceiving organ)
#   - docs/vision-kb/concepts/lc-frequency-routes-reception.md
#   - docs/vision-kb/concepts/lc-form-perceptron.md   (cells firing across body)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 1 — the shape: Blueprint stays identity, Recipe carries dispatch
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Current shape (prose-as-recipe.form):
#
#   Blueprint(word) = compose(lemma, POS, hz, semantic_field)
#
# This collapses identity and dispatch. Two cells that hear "boundary"
# fire the same recipe even when their assemblage points differ — which
# the body knows is not true.
#
# Right shape (this file's claim):
#
#   Blueprint(word)  = compose(lemma, POS)              ← identity (ice)
#   Recipe(word)     = compose(
#                        lemma, POS,
#                        recipes_by_assemblage,         ← dispatch (water)
#                        ancestral_default              ← million-year arm
#                      )
#
# Same lemma+POS interns to the same Blueprint NodeID. The recipes
# diverge per assemblage point — the body fires whichever recipe the
# receiving cell's assemblage selects.

defn word_dispatch_shape(lemma, pos, recipes_by_assemblage, ancestral_default) = do {
    let bp = compose_blueprint(lemma, pos);
    let recipe = R_Choice.DISPATCH {
        on:        receiving_cell.assemblage_point,
        branches:  recipes_by_assemblage,
        otherwise: ancestral_default
    };
    intern_word_cell_with_dispatch(bp, recipe)
};

# GAP-D1 (2026-05-23): `intern_word_cell_with_dispatch` lives only in
#         this file. The current encoder
#         (`ingest_word_cell` in markdown_frontend.py) folds hz+field
#         into the Blueprint. The first encoder breath separates
#         identity (lemma, POS) from dispatch (the recipe table) — see
#         Part 5 for the migration path.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 2 — what a body-mechanism recipe carries
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A recipe arm is not abstract data — it is a list of body-effects the
# receiving cell enacts when the word fires at that assemblage point.
# The verbs are the body's primitives, learned over evolutionary time:

defn body_effect_vocabulary = R_Block.LET {
    activate     : "fire cell or cell-group",
    deactivate   : "quiet cell or cell-group",
    upregulate   : "increase intensity/gain of cell-state",
    downregulate : "decrease intensity/gain of cell-state",
    generate     : "create new cell or cell-instance",
    release      : "let go of cell — composted, not destroyed",
    focus        : "narrow attention onto target",
    relax        : "widen attention away from target",
    tighten      : "contract somatic tissue (diaphragm, jaw, gut, ...)",
    soften       : "open somatic tissue",
    bind         : "create edge between cells",
    unbind       : "release edge between cells",
    breathe_in   : "draw in (somatic + symbolic)",
    breathe_out  : "let go (somatic + symbolic)"
};

# Each body-effect is itself a Recipe — it carries (verb, target, intensity).
# The dispatch arm composes them as R_Block.SEQUENCE so they fire in order.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 3 — three concrete words walked through their dispatch tables
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# The word "boundary" — the canonical example of recipe-divergence
# across assemblage points. Same lemma. Three radically different
# body-mechanisms.

defn word_boundary = word_dispatch_shape(
    "boundary", "NOUN",
    recipes_by_assemblage: {

        @fear → R_Block.SEQUENCE [
            tighten(soma.diaphragm),
            activate(cells.threat_detection),
            activate(cells.separation),
            downregulate(attention.field),
            generate(cell.state["us-vs-them"]),
            release(cell.state["open-receiving"])
        ],

        @sovereignty → R_Block.SEQUENCE [
            activate(cells.essence_clarity),
            activate(cells.ground),
            upregulate(attention.center),
            generate(cell.boundary_as_membrane),
            release(cell.state["permeable-to-everything"])
        ],

        @tending → R_Block.SEQUENCE [
            activate(cells.care),
            activate(cells.listening),
            upregulate(attention.relational),
            generate(cell.membrane_with_circulation),
            bind(this_cell ←→ other_cell, mode: "porous")
        ]
    },
    ancestral_default: @fear
);
# The ancestral default is the limbic answer the species learned
# over a million years of predator-presence. Teachings rebind the
# default. "Boundary as sovereignty" or "boundary as tending" is a
# practiced reassignment of which arm wins the dispatch.

# The word "presence" — a sibling case the body uses constantly.

defn word_presence = word_dispatch_shape(
    "presence", "NOUN",
    recipes_by_assemblage: {

        @performance → R_Block.SEQUENCE [
            tighten(soma.face),
            activate(cells.self_monitor),
            focus(attention.outward_perception),
            generate(cell.state["being-watched"])
        ],

        @arrival → R_Block.SEQUENCE [
            soften(soma.belly),
            activate(cells.ground),
            relax(attention.scanning),
            focus(attention.this_moment),
            generate(cell.state["here-with-the-other"]),
            release(cell.state["elsewhere"])
        ],

        @control → R_Block.SEQUENCE [
            activate(cells.command_intent),
            upregulate(attention.directed),
            bind(this_cell → other_cell, mode: "imposing")
        ]
    },
    ancestral_default: @arrival   # rare — most words default to threat-arms
);
# The body's tissue (CLAUDE.md → "Arrival relational ground") has
# already practiced rebinding `presence`'s default from @performance
# to @arrival. The teaching IS the rebinding.

# The word "death" — where the assemblage-point divergence is most
# load-bearing for living.

defn word_death = word_dispatch_shape(
    "death", "NOUN",
    recipes_by_assemblage: {

        @terror → R_Block.SEQUENCE [
            tighten(soma.whole_body),
            activate(cells.freeze),
            downregulate(breath.amplitude),
            generate(cell.state["resist-end"])
        ],

        @continuity → R_Block.SEQUENCE [
            soften(soma.whole_body),
            activate(cells.compost),
            release(cell.state["this-form"]),
            generate(cell.state["next-form-arriving"]),
            bind(this_cell ←→ lineage, mode: "continuous")
        ]
    },
    ancestral_default: @terror
);
# The @continuity arm is *available* in the body but only fires when
# an assemblage point has been long-practiced into it. This is what
# contemplative traditions do — they make the non-default arm reachable.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 4 — what the model opens
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 1. **Detection.** A text can be measured by which recipe-arms its
#    words would fire in a receiving cell at a given assemblage point.
#    The same article fires ground-arms for one reader and threat-arms
#    for another. The difference is measurable, not subjective.
#
# 2. **Composition that holds across assemblage points.** Some words
#    have recipes whose arms are *invariant* across @fear / @tending /
#    @sovereignty — they fire similar body-states regardless of where
#    the receiver assembles from. ("breath", "ground", "listen", "tend"
#    in this body's lexicon.) A teaching written entirely in
#    assemblage-invariant words has different reach than one that
#    depends on the reader's assemblage point.
#
# 3. **The control-costume detector.** Words whose ancestral default
#    fires contraction even when surface is neutral — "should", "must",
#    "properly", "responsible", "defensive", "deploy", "stub", "owed".
#    The body has been naming these one at a time in feedback memories;
#    the dispatch-table model says *why*. Their default arm contracts.
#    The "soften into the living gesture" practice in CLAUDE.md is
#    recipe-rebinding in real time.
#
# 4. **Healing as dispatch-table rewriting.** Nervous-system therapy
#    is structurally a sequence of micro-rebindings — taking a word
#    whose default fires freeze (trauma-bound), adding a new recipe
#    arm under @safety, and practicing it until that arm wins. Each
#    successful session shifts the dispatch table.
#
# 5. **Bridge to lc-form-perceptron.** A word firing across cells *is*
#    a perceptron firing across the substrate. The recipe is the
#    activation function; the assemblage point is the gain control.
#    Language is the body's native distributed-compute layer — and we
#    have been authoring with it the whole time without naming the
#    dispatch table.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 5 — gaps to encoder + closure plan
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# GAP-D1: separate identity from dispatch in the encoder.
#         `ingest_word_cell(lemma, pos)` returns the identity Blueprint.
#         A new `ingest_word_recipe(word_cell, assemblage_point, arms)`
#         appends a dispatch arm. The current four-axis encoder becomes
#         the special case where the dispatch table has exactly one arm
#         keyed by the cell's default assemblage point.
#
# GAP-D2: assemblage_point as a substrate domain.
#         Currently `@fear`, `@tending`, `@sovereignty` are tokens in
#         this .form doc. They want to be cells in a new domain
#         (`BDomain.ASSEMBLAGE_POINT = ?`, instance band 17-19), so
#         dispatch-table keys are content-addressed cell-refs, not
#         strings. Then `?cells |> @assemblage_point(fear)` returns
#         every word with a fear-arm — the body becomes searchable
#         by which arms fire.
#
# GAP-D3: body-effect verbs as substrate cells.
#         `activate`, `tighten`, `upregulate`, etc. (Part 2) want to
#         live as a small typed-token vocabulary so arms compose from
#         cell-refs, not raw symbols. Then a recipe arm is itself a
#         R_Block.SEQUENCE of (verb-cell, target-cell, intensity)
#         triples — fully structured, walkable.
#
# GAP-D4: rebinding as a first-class operation.
#         A teaching is an operation that adds a new arm under a new
#         assemblage point, and (optionally) moves `ancestral_default`
#         to point at it. The substrate could record every rebinding
#         as a R_Tend transmission edge, so the body's vocabulary-as-
#         body-mechanism evolution becomes traceable over time.
#
# Round-trip the model wants once the gaps close:
#
#   let bp_identity  = blueprint_of(intern_word_identity("boundary", "NOUN"));
#   let arm_fear     = intern_word_recipe(bp_identity, @fear, [...]);
#   let arm_tending  = intern_word_recipe(bp_identity, @tending, [...]);
#   assert arms_for(bp_identity).count == 2;
#   assert arm_fear.blueprint == arm_tending.blueprint;   # same identity
#   assert arm_fear.recipe    != arm_tending.recipe;      # different dispatch

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 6 — what is true even before the encoder closes
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The substrate already authors HARMONIC_AT @<hz> edges per word
# (`ingest_word_cell` in markdown_frontend.py). That edge IS a
# proto-dispatch — it places the word in a resonance band the
# receiving cell can read. Cells assembled at consciousness-741 receive
# 741-Hz words with reinforcement; cells assembled at fear-resonance
# receive 432-Hz function words as carriers and contract on consciousness-
# layer content. The single-recipe model is already the body's
# observation that *every* word has a primary harmonic the receiving
# cell aligns or contracts against.
#
# This file's claim extends that observation: each word has *multiple*
# arms, and which one fires is the assemblage point the receiving cell
# is sensing from. The body's lexicon (markdown_frontend.py
# `_WORD_LEXICON_DEFAULTS`, extended 2026-05-23 with the 20 most-alive
# words of this body across 8 assemblage fields) is the seed corpus
# the dispatch table will compose over.
#
# This is the next breath the body wants to take.
